    <title>Combined summary - Making Electrum more anonymous</title>
    <updated>2023-06-10T03:09:10.647220+00:00</updated>
    <link href="https://lists.linuxfoundation.org/pipermail/bitcoin-dev/2015-July/009512.html" rel="alternate"/>
    <summary>The article focuses on the issue of privacy in Bitcoin transactions and proposes different solutions to improve anonymity. One proposal is to combine all addresses a client is interested in into a single bloom filter or for the server to send a bloom filter of addresses in each block, but these proposals have not been convincing so far.Another suggestion is to create an anonymous routing layer between Electrum servers and clients inspired by TOR. This involves each server publishing an RSA public key, and each client receiving a list of available servers with their respective pubkeys. For each wallet address, the client selects a server and an RSA keypair, creates encrypted requests, and sends them to the main server. The main server dispatches the requests to the corresponding servers without revealing the client's IP address. However, implementing this scheme raises some weakness issues, such as lack of relay nodes making collaboration trivial, directory perpetual weakness, and content visibility to the exit node.The proposed system aims to provide anonymity for Electrum clients while using RSA encryption to secure communications between clients and servers. However, it would be too complicated in practice, and there would be many other types of attacks to defend against. Instead, it is suggested that better work on Electrum server defenses should be pursued, hardening them against denial-of-service attacks.The article also discusses different privacy options for query transactions in Bitcoin, such as IT-PIR protocol, computationally-bounded CPIR option, and stealth prefix queries. Prefix filtering enables client-tuning objectives and avoids server collusion attacks without being dependent on computational bounds. The primary trade-off is the size of the result set against privacy.Furthermore, the context suggests that valid solutions exist to address this problem, including introducing truly-random timing variations into mixnet solutions to mitigate timing attacks. However, trade-offs between privacy and performance are essential because the level of privacy will always be a performance trade-off.The issue of privacy in Bitcoin transactions has been a significant problem for the cryptocurrency's fungibility. While zero-knowledge proofs may come to the rescue, currently running a full chain wallet remains the only solution for maximum privacy, which is not practical in many scenarios.Finally, the article emphasizes the importance of privacy and anonymity in Electrum clients by encouraging server operators to make their servers reachable as tor hidden services, making sure server discovery works with .onion addresses, and making privacy a user-configurable setting. Overall, privacy in Bitcoin transactions remains a significant concern, and various proposals have been made to address the issue.</summary>
